a tiny piece from my new series. i wrote a poem to represent the artwork instead of an artist statement: one of our first concepts in life - mine. yet, somehow what is mine, as a girl, and now as a woman, had and has been: judged. moulded. lusted after. shaved. plucked. pushed. shamed. mine -stolen, conglomerated. a society obsessed. let them be shamed forever into silence... a door swings open. light crawls across the floor. she walks through. resilient. unscathed of the injustices that weighted on her foremothers. .

text: basta! basta de callar por temor, porque siempre nos hicieron creer que son ellos quienes tienen el control, que son ellos quienes tienen el poder, basta de soportar el morbo, los toqueteos, los celos enfermisos, las propuestas inapropiadas, basta de enfrentarnos entre nosotras, en vez de creernos y apoyarnos.lo que estamos viviendo como sociedad no es nuevo, lamentablemente 8 de cada 10 mujeres en el mundo sufren algun tipo de acoso, abuso y /o violacion  y muchas no pueden nisiquiera contarlo, parece una locura que cada dia aprarezca una mujer muerta por feminicidio, estamos permitiendo que esto se transforme en algo natural, si bien cada mujer tiene su proceso y su tiempo, no debemos quedarnos calladas, porque? porque si hablamos estamos de alguna manera impidiendo que le pase a alguien mas, hoy la mujer se animo y no solo en el ambito del espectaculo(#metoo #miracomonosponemos #niunamenos),muchas que de alguna manera hemos sido maltratadas  fisica y/o psicologicamente, independientemente del lugar en el que nos encontremos empezamos a alzar la voz, quiza necesitabamos esa contencion para sentirnos protegidas, para sentir que alguien nos creia, que otra se identificaba y no esta mal,porque al final la union es la que hace la fuerza.creemos y somos unas convencidas que el unico objetivo de estos movimientos  es apoyar y cambiar la situacion que hoy vive la otra, que puede estar sometida, silenciada, aqui no se trata de juzgar, ni seÃ±alar.animarse libera,te permite continuar, sacarte esa culpa innecesaria que creemos tener,porque ninguna mujer tendria que sentirse responsable  por el solo hecho de ser mujer.nadie tiene el derecho a robarte la felicidad,a creer que es dueÃ±o de tu vida,de tus sueÃ±os.nadie tiene el derecho a juzgarte como ser humano mucho menos como mujer, ni por lo que digas, ni por lo que pienses, ni por lo que hagas y mucho menos por lo que vistas.nadie tiene el derecho a menospreciarte, a torturarte emocionalmente, a clasificarte porque a un compaÃ±ero x se le ocurrio. eres valiosa, todas somos valiosisimas.dile hoy a ese abusador no pudiste conmigo, no arruinaste mi vida!sumate,denuncia y dile: yo puedo, lo hare, solo observame! ğŸ’ªğŸ’– #bastaya

text:
the nyt got this headline wrong. the money was for retaliation (being fired) for speaking up about being uncomfortable. unfortunately this will now lead to backlash of people saying you can get millions of dollars if you complain about a few jokes. retaliation is the true crime here. have we learned nothing? even if you think #metoo has gone too far (altho we've just scratched the surface), even if you think women are being 'overly sensitive' and annoying, how do you still "jokingly" say the word rape?! ever!!! chronic jokesters, and i believe @michaelmweatherly is in that category, need to learn some impulse control. get control of your mouth. words matter. thank god we are finally seeing brave people speaking up about this nonsense. @cbstvstudios has had a long run of huge success, but they have major work to do to regain respect. 
#metoo #timesup @timesupnow #womensupportingwomen #enoughisenough #growup @hruprise

text:
when i was a little girl i was creative, shy and i wanted to fly with paper wings i skillfully crafted.  despite being introverted, i had big plans.  i was going to carry my dadâ€™s larger than life ladder from the garage to the back of our ranch house, climb to the roof, attach the wings to my arms and jump while flapping my little arms as fast as they could go. 
i dreamt night after night about the amazing things i would see once i finished my wings and took flight.  as i'm writing this, i still remember that feeling of pure joy and wonderment.  luckily, for my own safety, i couldnâ€™t manage to even move the big ladder so i had to resort to the next highest flight platform, the picnic table! i jumped and flapped as hard as i could and when i fell straight to the ground i went right back to the drawing board planning new and improved wing concepts. - excerpt from my book, you glow, girl!

i'm still building my wings, but just in different ways now and they are always new and improved taking me higher and higher. i know itâ€™s not easy but donâ€™t let the fear of falling keep you from flying!  when a bird is sitting on a tree she's not afraid of he branch breaking because her trust isn't in the branch, it's in her wings.  always believe in yourself and fly high!  xo

text:
fans of k-pop supergroup bts was the top fandom community on instagram in 2018, according to a recent press release from the image-sharing platform.

known to be among the most active fandoms online, the â€œbts armyâ€ showcased their devotion and loyalty to their beloved boy band on the site, vogue reports.

it was a huge year for the k-pop group. they recently developed a successful collaboration with nicki minaj, addressed the united nations, and, as of thursday, remained at the top of the billboard social 50 chart for 104 weeks.

they also received a nomination at the 61st annual grammy awards for their third korean studio album, â€œlove yourself: tear.â€ while the site did not reveal the data on the most-followed accounts in 2018 like in previous years, the top trends on the platform were not much of a surprise.

aside from bts and their fandom, the only other celebrity to make it to one of the top results for instagram this year was drake, although it was mainly due to the #inmyfeelingschallenge trend that went viral.

instagram also revealed that its top advocacy hashtags were #metoo, #marchforourlives, and #timesup.

meanwhile, asmr (autonomous sensory meridian response) was named the top niche community trend on the site.

disneyland tokyo was also named the â€œhappiest geotagged location in the world,â€ which simply meant they received the highest use of the ğŸ™‚smiley emoji in instagram usersâ€™ captions.

text:
it's taken years to deactivate the land mines in my body and psyche he planted.  siren whispers seductively in the innermost caverns of my mind..."you and your body are bad...how dare you be free of me." the life or death threats took dominion over my nervous system...comply, accommodate or die.  the routes well worn carving into...shredding...the freedom of my heart to love. love myself. love my body. love others. love men. love pleasure. love desire. how dare i be free? i dare. to be free. in my body, in my eros, in my creativity and pleasure.  i dare to love deep, wide and true.  it's taken 48 years. 48 years.  all the things that come with sexual abuse have occupied...visited my life...self hatred, shame, eating disorders, perfection, hiding, masking, appearing better than i am and worse.  and here i am. still here. alive, creative, connected. inhabiting my body. the  price of healing...everything.  it took everything. is it worth it? today i say yes.  yes...there is the other side of #metoo (thank you and reverence for #metoo founder and steward tarana burke). the healing into wholeness.  the scars are there.  the vulnerability.  the pockets in my psyche that still beckon to me...inviting me to the downward spiral of shame.  i can choose now.  sovereignty is available in this being body now.

and there are gifts given for having taken this life long journey. it's not over. and it is a new day.  claiming my birthright freedom of expression, of existence, of the capacity to love who and how and when i want may just be the most important contribution to our collective healing i can make. "we have been raised to fear the yes within ourselves, our deepest cravings. but, once recognized, those which do not enhance our future lose their power and can be altered.  the fear of our desires keeps them suspect and indiscriminately powerful, for to suppress any truth is to give it strength beyond endurance.  the fear that we cannot grow beyond whatever distortions we may find within ourselves keep us docile and loyal and obedient, externally defined, and leads to accept many facets of our oppression as women.  recognizing the power of the erotic within our lives can
name: Anakha Coman

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
strangulation and suffocation are both tactics used by perpetrators to exert power and control. the inability to breathe is one of the most terrorizing experiences a person can experience and is a sign of increasingly violent abuse. suffocation can go unreported because of the physical trauma - hypoxia, the lack of oxygen flow to the brain, can cause brain damage and memory loss.
.
documenting abuse, communicating with a friend or domestic violence advocate, and seeking professional medical help are a all methods that survivors can use to stay safe.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i've decided to finally come and post this on instagram as well. 
i originally posted this on my twitter because i have been stalked, harassed, and mentally abused by this man for the last 5 years and it went a step too far when he started reaching out to harass my friends. 
i posted this in november and since then he has tried to "flip the situation" and say that my claims of assault are not true, and that i was the one who sexually assaulted him. his obsession and instability has gone overboard now and he's made multiple different accounts claiming i'm a sexual predator and is even trying to get my career involved. 
while i was assaulted, i do believe what was done was a smaller scale issue and i had no intention of speaking about until the stalking, suicide threats, harrassment, and manipulation began. i also don't believe this is an issue outside of the cosplay/con community so i won't be releasing his full name or other info about him. while i'm doing this as some closure for myself i also want to make sure other women in the community stay stay safe and avoid him at all costs. he's proven to have obsessive tendencies of any woman he catches feelings for and i do not want anyone else to have to go to through what i have. 
#cosplay #ala #animelosangeles #animeexpo #metoo #stalker #harassment #assault #californiaconventions #ala2019
name: Nikki

.
'god rest ye merry gentlemen' = anti-feminist
.

.
'blue christmas' = implies male/boy righteousness
.

.

.

.
and last but not least....
.
'i saw mommy kissing santa claus' = promotes adultery
.
if this offends anyone, please donâ€™t bother to tell me as i just donâ€™t care. i drink coffee stronger than your feelings."
.
.
.

he was the director of a large organization who had just delivered a speech to my college class. iâ€™m a soon-to-be college grad whoâ€™s looking for a job in marketing. and he had a position available that was right up my alley.

as it turned out, the job was rightâ€”but the situation was all wrong. he, a businessman more than 30 years older than me, was "attracted" to more than just the luster of my intellect, experience, and skill set.

let me share with you what happened that day. after his presentation was over, i approached him to ask a few questions about his organization. we decided to grab a table to sit down and continue the conversation.

i sat down, and then he took the chair right next to meâ€”on the same side of the four-seater table. i found it a bit strange, but i continued on with our conversation, which soon turned to the position he was trying to fill.

his next move was to put his arm around me. i leaned forward to separate the physical touch and continued with what i was saying. i was uncomfortable, but i wanted to learn more, so i went along with the conversation, pushing his uncomfortable gestures out of my mind.

but it didnâ€™t end there. as he was giving me his business card, he flipped it over and wrote his home address. then, he invited me over on the weekendâ€”an offer that disoriented me so much i couldnâ€™t even speak. a few minutes later, as we were leaving, i went to shake his handâ€”and he ignored me and kissed me on the top of my head.

we parted ways, and i drove off with a swirling mind and a turning stomach. i was hurt and annoyed, and i was frustrated by the fact that my attempts to forge a professional connection were treated this way. why did he think this was acceptable? why did he push the boundaries so far?

text:
i am so excited to have the amazing jazz egger on gratitude:unfiltered today at 12pm pacific! 
jazz egger is an international model, actress and music journalist from austria. she moved to london when she was 18 years old.

in 2013, she competed in the final of elite model look, the world's most prestigious modeling contest.  in november 2016, jazz recaptioned her instagram photos using the hashtag #truthbehindthisshot and hundreds of magazines featured her story, worldwide. 
a few months after her hashtag went viral, she produced #truthbehindthisshot part 2, a campaign in which she shows what her modeling photos look like completely unretouched. 
jazz article about image modeling and the darker sides of the fashion industry went viral. 
in that article she described the sketchy offers models receive, such as having to sleep with famous actors and get paid thousands of dollars for it. 
she is known and celebrated worldwide for being an activist and being a voice for women, in and outside the fashion industry. 
jazz is represented by several agencies all around the world.

a special thank you pstv today and iheartradio for broadcasting this show! #modelwithpurpose #friday #gratitudeğŸ™ #unfiltered #jazzegger #iheartradio #pstv

text: been thinking a lot about the #metoo movement and what we can all do to hold ourselves accountable. when sexual assault, harassment, or misconduct occur, we often talk about it with our friends. often, it gets normalized, brushed off. "oh yeah, haha, he's just like that" or "yeah he did that to me once." this is not okay. many victims are too scared to speak for themselves. we minimize what happened in our heads and make it smaller than it was. we think we're crazy, overreacting. this is not true. we are not crazy. we are hurt. if a friend ever comes to you, hold yourself accountable. they have trusted you with their experience, their memories. make sure they feel safe. make sure they feel heard. make sure you take action when they can't, when they're too scared to. if this happens in the workplace, make sure the right people get involved. help them. help us. this is not normal and we should not treat it as such. we need to lean on each other. to all women and men, i say: i will be your safe place. i will be there for you. i will make sure you feel heard. i hope everyone else follows suit.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
#metoo 
ever since i was a little girl i have always had the ability to make friends easily and have forged many incredible bonds throughout my life. whether it's for a lifetime or just for a moment in time, each of these friendships have added meaning to my life. i always want the best for others and i always try to only see the best in everyone. throughout my journey i have met some incredible people, many of whom i now call friend but many of whom began to add toxicity to my recovery and i needed to block from my life. but it's not only these newer friendships that sometimes bring toxicity to my recovery, sometimes it's from people i considered my friend long before my illness began, leaving me no choice but to block them from my life as well for the sake of my wellbeing. even if i always want the best for others and i always try to only see the best in everyone, sometimes i just need to "choose me" because i can only save one person at a time. last night i was left feeling a little more broken by one of these friendships when i became a victim of sexual harassment. it left me feeling ashamed, afraid, sad, anxious, guilty, hurt and angry until i eventually cried myself to sleep. i don't cope well with any of these emotions and noone has the right to make anyone feel any of these emotions ever, whether it's from a stranger, a relative, a co-worker, or a friend. 
#metoo #youarenotalone #kindness #ichooseme

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
what if you took a moment, right now, to construct a list of everything that you are proud of. 
everything that you love about yourself. everything that you have battled, overcome, and ultimately developed from. 
what if you took a moment, right now, to do so?

take a moment to remind yourself of how capable you are of achieving so many beautiful things. how, what ever your biggest dreams may be, there is not a single thing that states you are not good enough, strong enough, smart enough. 
what if you made a point of doing this more often?

reminding yourself that even though there may be things lacking in your life, there are many more important things that are already present to be grateful for.

that we only have so much energy in a day, and we should try to contribute it towards doing good as supposed to pondering on the bad. 
that every portion of who you were created to be is an irreplaceable addition to this universe. 
that your hard work will pay off, and you truly make such a huge difference. 
please, take a moment to remind yourself. remind yourself of these beautiful aspects of living, your world, and who you are as a person.

this is why i share my journey.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
ok, i might ruffle some feathers and i am ok with that, as long as i can get people to look at things in a different light.
lately i keep hearing how we need to remove things, people, history so we can show we are strong, empowered and respected. how many times do we hear, that song makes women look wrong, remove it; or you canâ€™t talk to your ex because it means you still want them? how about remove a piece of history because itâ€™s degrading? i am all about respect, honor, strength, empowering ourselves and others, but i see a huge flaw in how we are trying to get it! respect, honor, strength and feeling empowered starts in one place, in ourselves. we can remove everything and it will not solve the problem. learn to love yourself and find those things in you. stop giving outside influences the power to verify you. if you are a strong, independent, empowered individual, a song is just a song. if you are in a healthy, happy, secure relationship where each person is happy and secure with themselves, nothing can break that bind. itâ€™s so easy for us to look for an excuse or something to blame; when we do this, we give our power away. take it back and realize nothing justifies you but you. be who you want to be without needing someone else to change or something to be removed. we are all strong, independent, beautiful, empowered, unique individuals! hold your head up and be proud of who you are now!!! #empowered #strong #beauty #loveyourself #metoo #lovelife #80dayobsession #fitness #trueself #weightlifting

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
year in music: the slow road to music's #metoo moment

year in music: the slow road to music's #metoo moment by hanif abdurraqib december 13, 2018, 12:01pm est
when kesha performed at the grammy awards in january, janelle monÃ¡e introduced her by talking about the time's up movement: â€œit's not just going on in hollywood, it's not just going on in washington [d.c.], it's right here in our industry as well.â€ kesha -- backed by cyndi lauper , camila cabello , andra day and others, all wearing white -- sang â€œpraying,â€ her anthem that centered on her yearslong legal battle with former producer lukasz â€œdr. lukeâ€ gottwald. â€œprayingâ€ was a triumphant reclamation of the singer's power and narrative, and among fans and on social media, it felt as if a wave of change might finally be coming to the music biz.
the #metoo movement has profoundly affected the film and tv industries, and accused men who try to restart their careers are often met with disdain (e.g., louis c.k.). in music, such men seem to have an easier time of it. in 2017, three years after kesha leveled her accusations against him, gottwald co-produced pop sensation kim petras â€™ debut single. in may 2017, antonio â€œl.a.â€ reid left sony music following a sexual harassment claim by an assistant. within months, he raised $75 million for a revival of his hitco entertainment company. the label has signed artists including big boi and dinah jane of fifth harmony .
others are less public, but possibly biding their time for a comeback: charlie walk, former president of universal music groupâ€™s republic group, parted ways with the label in march after adamantly denying several allegations of sexual misconduct. after 11 women made allegations including rape and sexual assault against music mogul russell simmons, he stepped down from all of his companies last fall, but on nov. 7 tweeted a sketch of women on a pink background with the caption, â€œwomen win.â€
discussions about misogyny in music are often about lyrics, or the artists who fans love despite their misdeeds. still, the industry tends to overlook how https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2018/8489958/metoo-movement-music-industry-year-in-music-2018

text:
since the banning of "baby its cold outside" in light of the #metoo movement, please boycott the christmas song "i want a hippopotamus for christmas" because it exploits endangered hippos. while we are at it the same goes for: "santa claus is coming to town" = fake news "little drummer boy" = gender neutral "white christmas" = racist and xenophobic "o' come all ye faithful" = exclusive "god rest ye merry gentlemen" = anti-feminist "all i want for christmas is you" = stalking "blue christmas" = implies male/boy righteousness "the 12 days of christmas" = anti-semitic (8 days) "santa baby" = reverse #metoo and exploits handouts "o little town of bethlehem" = pro jew and xenophobic "winter wonderland" = dismisses wonderlands that don't have winter "its the most wonderful time of the year" = exclusive against 4th of july and summer "let it snow" = not fair to those where it does not snow "do you hear what i hear" = insensitive to hearing impaired

and last but not least.... "i saw mommy kissing santa claus" = promotes adultery

if this offends anyone, please donâ€™t bother to tell me as i just donâ€™t care. copy and paste if you agree!

and last but not least.... "i saw mommy kissing santa claus" = promotes adultery

had the pleasure of introducing @mayssakaraa at her simple cure campaign launch with a spoken word performance.

when artists combine...man, watch out.

most powerful realization of 2017 was that i was an artist.

most powerful realization of 2018 was "how to be a firestarter". the beauty of becoming something greater is that it opens the door to greater opportunity.

the challenge is that it requires more of you.

you must become something greater to achieve something greater. so if you ain't growing...you ain't going. comprende?

text:
ah
ah

doo, doo, doo, doo, doo, doo
doo, doo, doo, doo, doo, doo, doo

don't you wonder sometimes
bout sound and vision?

blue, blue, electric blue
that's the color of my room
where i will live
blue, blue

pale blinds drawn all day
nothing to do, nothing to say
blue, blue

i will sit right down
waiting for the gift of sound and vision
and i will sing
waiting for the gift of sound and vision
drifting into my solitude
over my head

don't you wonder sometimes
bout sound and vision?

david bowie

text:
i just had an awesome skype talk about scars with dee schmidt kramer's students who read scars as an independent reading book at silver creek high school in indiana. the students asked such intelligent, thoughtful questions afterwards. i told them they could ask me anything and i meant it.

and despite some technical difficulties - i couldn't see or hear them on skype but they could see and hear me - it went really well. dee helped solve it in a creative way, using her cell so i could see the students, typing their questions in skype, and one student turned dee's cell to landscape mode so i could see them all.

i talked about self-harm and why i used it to cope, and myths about self-harm; being queer in a homophobic world; being a sexual abuse survivor; and how i hoped to increase compassion and awareness about those issues through scars (and from reader letters, i know i have). i also discussed how much books have helped me, including publishing my own, and especially all the reader letters i receive, told them that my arm is on the cover of scars, and when one of them asked why i hadn't written a book about petal yet, i was happy to tell them that petal is in my new manuscript! (grinning)

i enjoyed it so much. i could see them taking it all in, and caring about it. i delight in readers caring about books - and authors!

petal also made an appearance! (laughing) she's always by my side, and at the end when i picked her up and she rested her head on my shoulder they awwed. (smiling)
.
.
.

i just had an awesome skype talk about scars with dee schmidt kramer's students who read scars as an independent reading book at silver creek high school in indiana. the students asked such intelligent, thoughtful questions afterwards. i told them they could ask me anything and i meant it.

and despite some technical difficulties - i couldn't see or hear them on skype but they could see and hear me - it went really well. dee helped solve it in a creative way, using her cell so i could see the students, typing their questions in skype, and one student turned dee's cell to landscape mode so i could see them all.

i talked about self-harm and why i used it to cope, and myths about self-harm; being queer in a homophobic world; being a sexual abuse survivor; and how i hoped to increase compassion and awareness about those issues through scars (and from reader letters, i know i have). i also discussed how much books have helped me, including publishing my own, and especially all the reader letters i receive, told them that my arm is on the cover of scars, and when one of them asked why i hadn't written a book about petal yet, i was happy to tell them that petal is in my new manuscript! (grinning)

i enjoyed it so much. i could see them taking it all in, and caring about it. i delight in readers caring about books - and authors!

petal also made an appearance! (laughing) she's always by my side, and at the end when i picked her up and she rested her head on my shoulder they awwed. (smiling)
.
.
.

#barbietoo  before i left the house i made sure to dress in something loose that would not be too distracting. as i walk the streets of new york at night,one hand holds my groceries tightly, the other holds my pocket knife. i walk with urgency, my hoodie is up and my headphones in and,which are not playing music, act like a barrier between the men who catcalls and whistles at me. i see a masculine shadow at the end of the street, but i cannot see its owner. i fear itâ€™s a man awaiting my passing. i make a detour and walk across the street. 
as i usually do on a weekend night, i was clubbing and hanging out with my girls. i normally go to gay clubs, but this weekend i went to a straight club.  once i felt a strong grip on my ass, i turned around to say what the hell, but this 6 foot tall frat guy in a polo would not look at me. this is the first time i  had my ass grabbed unsolicitedly. they have the balls to grab me, but they donâ€™t own up to their actions. every 5 minutes i would take a headcount of my girls because the cocky boys would not listen to us when we said we did not want to grind with them. this was the first night where i saw that the boys were not listening to no. it made me wonder why they felt because it was dark and the music was loud that they could do what they want. i was not being listened to. â€œthere is no greater threat to women than men? weâ€™re the number one threat!â€ said louis c.k. in his hbo special. when are men taught to acknowledge boundaries? i should be able to leave and feel safe wherever i go without having to worry. i am tired with the way that men are treating me and other women. every women has there own story with harassment, but to tell mine i am using barbie as my proxy. when i was younger i looked up to her and she was a beacon of indepence and i vividly remember watching rapunzel barbie in my bubblegum pink room thinking â€œlook at all that she can do for herselfâ€. #photo #photography #art #camera #canon #fujifilm #fujitx1 #digital #digitalphoto #digitalphotography #digitalphotos #mirrorless #metoo #barbie #pink #hair #violent #ken #sexualassult

text: i'm fine. these issues have been brought up because they need to be addressed and only because improvements need to be made. before writing it all out i've always been quiet and well, mouse. i understand that's not ever going to be the same. i'd like to hold onto the shred of humanity i have left. not get badgered in good or bad ways. grateful for what i have in life, for surviving. for the few people who talk to me like a person, that's really important. for homey golden little pony boy who's been holding me down through the adventure, all wild and free like. i'm not the face of rape, my name is kelsey and it's be nice if i can continue to grow rather than being put back there. haven't done that yet, won't do it now, just feel like that more than necessary. eminem and xzibit dont approach me describes it well.  #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #toomuchclout #nomanhasclaimonmylife #nojusticenopeace

text:
we ache for connection.  we ache for truth and to be seen.  and heard. 
a couple of months ago i was in north carolina in an uber and talking to the driver, he said that heâ€™d been working for days and no one had engaged in a conversation. 
just in talking to him and asking about his life realized how often i disappear into the little white box in front of me.  at first books were an introverts best friend, and now the phone. 
real connection, where we meet eyes and match heartbeats is more and more rare- i have my phone up for a week during retreat a couple of weeks ago.  and then i noticed just how little real conversation was happening.  when i got the phone back it didnâ€™t take long for me to get right back in.  so now, putting the phone down is a practice.  connecting is a practice.  however awkward for me itâ€™s just as important as my meditation or morning dance party. 
fuck it.  the message can wait, the text will get sent.  call it connection or co-regulating it heart meeting- letâ€™s connect irl. 
iâ€™ll start with eye contact, sister.  then letâ€™s tell the truth.  and dance.  will you meet me?

text: (2/4) in undergrad, there are a whole bunch of personalities put together in a small place. and it was then that i realized i needed to find my own identity. but college was a life-changingly difficult time for me. without going into all the details, i didnâ€™t receive proper and appropriate counseling and help for dealing with a toxic relationship, i lost touch with friends because of it, and i struggled to keep up with classes. furthermore, sophomore year i lost my grandmother, and junior year i lost 3 classmates in a car accident. i became so concerned for my personal safety that at one point, i left in the middle of the night. when the #metoo movement broke out shortly after i left, i took comfort in seeing my school struggling to right the wrongs of their past.

text:
why the camellia in my motherâ€™s garden is a badass
it was thanksgiving day and it was cold. 
all the other flowers were dead and gone, wimped out with the first frost. 
but not this showstopper. 
not only was this bright pink camellia in my motherâ€™s garden gorgeous in spite of the cold, she was gorgeous because of it. 
camellias need winter. 
they need the cold to strut their stuff. 
if the bright pink camellia in my motherâ€™s garden could talk, i think sheâ€™d flip her hair back and share the secret of how to find your mojo in the middle of a cold, dead season. 
and i think sheâ€™d leave us with this quote by albert camus: â€œin the midst of winter, i finally learned that there was within me an invincible summer.â€
sistersâ€”be a camellia. 
use the tough stuff, the abuse, the abandonment, the harsh words, the criticism, the  negativity, all the winter life throws at us, and bloom, dangitall. 
winter can kill you if you let it. 
but it can also make you a badass. 
i choose in the midst of winter, to find my invincible summer. 
how bout you? 
#camellias #inthemidstofwinter #albertcamus #badasswomen #bloomwhereyouareplanted #overcome #trauma #findyourself #findyourmuchness #metoo #metoomovement #lovewins

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words, every day.

the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and keep abusing the faith of their fellow men. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

one of the remarkable elements the trans-siberian train was the wagon-chapelle, a traveling russian orthodox church. staffed by russian orthodox priests, the train travelled from station to station, making up for the shortage of local churches in siberia. it was equipped with ringing bells at the end of the skylight to summon the faithful when approaching stations.â €

text:
the awareness on the topic of sexual violence is very essential. the former british foreign secretary, william hague, and the hollywood actress who is famous for her activism, angelina jolie, started the project aiming to bring awareness in this far-reaching issue. *
*
*

this project had a very big start and several goals were already reached. according to william hague, this project had an impact on making un pass security council resolutions on preventing sexual violence, including getting 155 nations to sign up to action on the issue at the general assembly. also, their work helped to gather young and global filmmakers to discuss the representations of sexual violence and its effects.
*
*
*

icdo supports the work of william hague and angelina jolie and stresses the importance of the project.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
i have been absent from social media for a couple of weeks now. my closest friends and i went through hell for the 6 longest days when our dear friend went missing. our beautiful carla went to costa rica to celebrate her 36 birthday to never return. on november 27 she stopped responding to calls and messages, and on december 5, her family members were able to identify her body and give the world the devastating news that our beloved friend was gone. 
the security guard at the @airbnb in san jose was the beast that took her from us. he is in custody at the moment, but the investigation keeps going. 
violence against women is a devastating very real issue. and girls like her that love to travel and enjoy life, pay the highest price. 
if you want to follow up with carlaâ€™s story, you can visit the facebook page we created to share her story: finding carla.

text:
cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

prior to the companyâ€™s role on trumpâ€™s election campaign, wylie had been its director of research. recalling his first meeting with bannon, he explained how fashion was one of the many things they examined, along with â€œjudith butler, foucault and nature of our fractured selfâ€. he said the pair discussed the difference between crocs and chanelâ€™s little black dress as analogous for the fashion spectrum â€“ which would become a blueprint for how the firm used fashion preferences later on.

wylie went onto to criticise the fashion industry for creating a â€œpre-existing cultural foundation which allowed the alt-right to grow over that time periodâ€. he conceded that while cambridge analytica â€œexploited the cultural narratives that the fashion and culture industry put outâ€, the fashion industry was responsible for creating those cultural narratives in the first place. he added: â€œwe need new narratives in culture, and to do a better job of showing more diversityâ€ in order to direct politics along a different route.

according to the data obtained (the majority of which came from us users), certain fans of american denim brands such as wrangler, hollister and lee jeans could be more closely linked to low levels of openness and mistrust â€“ and therefore more likely to engage with pro-trump messaging.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

prior to the companyâ€™s role on trumpâ€™s election campaign, wylie had been its director of research. recalling his first meeting with bannon, he explained how fashion was one of the many things they examined, along with â€œjudith butler, foucault and nature of our fractured selfâ€. he said the pair discussed the difference between crocs and chanelâ€™s little black dress as analogous for the fashion spectrum â€“ which would become a blueprint for how the firm used fashion preferences later on.

wylie went onto to criticise the fashion industry for creating a â€œpre-existing cultural foundation which allowed the alt-right to grow over that time periodâ€. he conceded that while cambridge analytica â€œexploited the cultural narratives that the fashion and culture industry put outâ€, the fashion industry was responsible for creating those cultural narratives in the first place. he added: â€œwe need new narratives in culture, and to do a better job of showing more diversityâ€ in order to direct politics along a different route.

according to the data obtained (the majority of which came from us users), certain fans of american denim brands such as wrangler, hollister and lee jeans could be more closely linked to low levels of openness and mistrust â€“ and therefore more likely to engage with pro-trump messaging.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

i am not a human being. i am a problem, a nuisance, an inconvenience. how dare i stand up for myself and countless other young men that have been sexually abused in the name of â€œartistic expressionâ€. in another interview done by wwd, hercules mag co-owner david vivirido, when asked about sexual assault accusations said, â€œof course itâ€™s not the same as someone accused of something like rapeâ€..... let that sink in real deep. so as long as you donâ€™t rape anybody, you have a place in fashion. this is precedent being set by people in power in such a close knit industry. controlled by a powerful few. -

so my question is, how many young men and women need to come forward for a change to happen? how many lives that have been broken due to the abuse suffered at the hands of photographers, casting directors, and agents will it take for something to be done?? -

i also hope that at some point we will have something else to talk about. because iâ€™m sick and tired of talking about men with power and influence, preying on the vulnerable. iâ€™m sick and tired of talking about people in a position to do something about it, standing by and doing nothing. 
truth is inevitable, and change is coming.

text:
cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

prior to the companyâ€™s role on trumpâ€™s election campaign, wylie had been its director of research. recalling his first meeting with bannon, he explained how fashion was one of the many things they examined, along with â€œjudith butler, foucault and nature of our fractured selfâ€. he said the pair discussed the difference between crocs and chanelâ€™s little black dress as analogous for the fashion spectrum â€“ which would become a blueprint for how the firm used fashion preferences later on.

wylie went onto to criticise the fashion industry for creating a â€œpre-existing cultural foundation which allowed the alt-right to grow over that time periodâ€. he conceded that while cambridge analytica â€œexploited the cultural narratives that the fashion and culture industry put outâ€, the fashion industry was responsible for creating those cultural narratives in the first place. he added: â€œwe need new narratives in culture, and to do a better job of showing more diversityâ€ in order to direct politics along a different route.

according to the data obtained (the majority of which came from us users), certain fans of american denim brands such as wrangler, hollister and lee jeans could be more closely linked to low levels of openness and mistrust â€“ and therefore more likely to engage with pro-trump messaging.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

text:
dear writer girl,

your words never failed to amaze me, every time you held the pen. the ink your quill spills might not leave an everlasting splash on others but for me, it's as indelible as for the sheet.

it's been awhile since we had coffee by my balcony.
i'd look at the setting sun and try to contemplate on life and you'd be there, smiling with my t-shirt on... staring at me, capturing every particular detail which even the almighty might have missed.

i've seen you fighting with words in order to give the perfect justice to the way i kissed you, how you caressed my hair whilst i rested my head on your lap, how badly you wanted to hide yourself within my arms on seeing a cockroach while i'd be busy being grateful to the creature.

sometimes i felt, your words were too exquisite to be true but the facade was too charming to be ignored. "words do turn me on!", i know i told you when we met for the first time and it was the first time that our eyes actually met and our cheeks went red. but...was it the crave for words? or some form of mutual...rather real existence, out of your scripted world.
i know you could muse a dozen set of verse for me but was being real too difficult?

love,
not so a writer guy.

sourav dey
(@quill_and_paper)
.
.
.

text:
[caption]
.
we were touched inappropriately when we didn't even know what it meant.
when we were gripped with fear that if we spoke to strangers they would take us away in their sacks,
we dared not to open our lips in front of people,
we weren't sacked,
but we were abused.
we didn't know what their intentions were. but , we just knew that they touched our body.
we were asked to send nudes when we didn't even know what they would do with it.
we were sent nudes with a long message describing the aftermath . and guess what, we didn't even know the terms.
at home , when everything was meant to be the safe . 
our relatives had other plans.
tutors had their parts too , tricking with punishments and having their share of pleasure .
and now when we look back ,we get aware of how we dealt with it in the past. 
we have forgotten the past but we remember our experiences.
we always look forward to the new day. to the new society. to a day when we would not say it out of bravery  but we would say it with our conscience within -
"we aren't afraid of men anymore."
.
follow- @words.in.symphony to read more from us.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
8 years and till infinity.
.
people say, the most beautiful feature in oneself is their smile. but there should be a reason for smiling.
lavleen kaur @lavleen26.kaur is one such reason for my smile.
we used to travel by same school bus and this is how we became friends. and we are best-friends since then.

you know why best? not everyone deserves this best title. she deserves because she is the one who knows me-
from fighting with me to fighting for me,
from sharing tiffins to sharing the title of best-friends,
from crying for me to crying with me,
from sitting on the same bench to sitting on my lap,
from crying on my shoulders to wiping those tears with my handkerchief,
she has always been the best.

someone who has walked my ways,
who knows my everyday pain.
someone who sometimes makes me a cry baby,
who meets me after long and becomes a cry baby.
even if time itself comes to an end
i'll be there for you till eternity.
you always put me first if i need you to be there,
someone lovable like you is really rare.

i love you @lavleen26.kaur (ğŸ‚)ğŸ˜‚ â¤ï¸
.
tag your best friend in the comment section and show some love ğŸ’—
.

if there is a person who brought some meaningful changes in your life, then let's pay a tribute to her/him right here at @shespeaksforthechange.

we all need such people around us afterall, don't we?

text:
#57 ciwit [3]
.
"ciwit yeuh ciwit (cubit nih cubit)," iseng si kakak pada adiknya. si adik yang menurut perkiraan saya berumur 3 tahun hanya bisa menepis. sesekali dia paksa kakaknya mundur. tapi si kakak tak mudah menyerah, tubuhnya yang sedikit lebih besar terus berupaya.
.
bersama si ibu, mereka menumpang kereta dari manggarai menuju selatan. bersebelahan duduk dengan saya semalam. si ibu berdiri di depan kami. tak banyak menggubris keisengan si anak. hanya diam, kosong, menatap jendela.
.
si adik perempuan tersenyum kecut, mulai kesal. dia malah memeluk kakaknya. "manis sekali," batin saya. si kakak bermuka bulat dengan bisul di atas mata, jidat, dan ujung lengan mulai tenang. dia menunjuk luka koreng di dengkul sang adik. "perih teu (perih tidak)?". si adik menggeleng. luka si adik tidak hanya itu. saya perhatikan ada setidaknya 4 luka bekas bisul di kaki, betis, dan paha. semua masih basah.
.
dari mana mereka? menuju pulang kah? mengapa si ibu membawa banyak barang? belanjaan atau...?
.
"umi, bapa ka mana (ibu, bapak ke mana)?", tetiba si adik melontarkan tanya di tengah padatnya penumpang kereta. si adik menatap jendela dan orang-orang bersliweran di setiap stasiun perhentian.
.
"teu aya bapa, geus mangkat. bapa maneh gelo (tidak ada bapak, sudah pergi. bapak kamu gila)", jawab si ibu dengan benci yang begitu dalam.
.
"ada yang mau lihat upin - ipin? ini pegang hp aku. yuk nonton yuk." ingin saya memeluk mereka. mengajaknya bermain bersama aimaruna. sepanjang perjalanan mereka menikmati tontonan itu. sayang, saya harus turun di depok lama. tapi semoga itu sedikit membasuh luka.
.
"terima kasih", ucap ibu mereka. saya tersenyum sambil melihat wajah lelahnya.
.
semoga kisah di ujung sana tidak seburuk pikir saya. ada doa menyelip dalam batin agar mereka terus kuat bersama.[]
.
ğŸ“· poem by rupi kaur

bersama si ibu, mereka menumpang kereta dari manggarai menuju selatan. bersebelahan duduk dengan saya semalam. si ibu berdiri di depan kami. tak banyak menggubris keisengan si anak. hanya diam, kosong, menatap jendela.
.
si adik perempuan tersenyum kecut, mulai kesal. dia malah memeluk kakaknya. "manis sekali," batin saya. si kakak bermuka bulat dengan bisul di atas mata, jidat, dan ujung lengan mulai teg. dia menunjuk luka koreng di dengkul sang adik. "perih teu (perih tidak)?". si adik menggeleng. luka si adik tidak hanya itu. saya perhatikan ada setidaknya 4 luka bekas bisul di kaki, betis, dan paha. semua masih basah.
.
dari mana mereka? menuju pulang kah? mengapa si ibu membawa banyak barang? belanjaan atau...?
.
"umi, bapa ka mana (ibu, bapak ke mana)?", tetiba si adik melontarkan tanya di tengah padatnya penumpang kereta. si adik menatap jendela dan orang-orang bersliweran di setiap stasiun perhentian.
.
"teu aya bapa, geus mangkat. bapa maneh gelo (tidak ada bapak, sudah pergi. bapak kamu gila)", jawab si ibu dengan benci yang begitu dalam.
.
"ada yang mau lihat upin - ipin? ini pegang hp aku. yuk nonton yuk." ingin saya memeluk mereka. mengajaknya bermain bersama aimaruna. sepanjang perjala mereka menikmati tonto itu. sayang, saya harus turun di depok lama. tapi semoga itu sedikit membasuh luka.
.
"terima kasih", ucap ibu mereka. saya tersenyum sambil melihat wajah lelahnya.
.
semoga kisah di ujung sana tidak seburuk pikir saya. ada doa menyelip dalam batin agar mereka terus kuat bersama.[]
.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
even when you feltÂ you weren't strong enough to survive, somehow you found the strength to survive anyway.Â - nikita gill
my smile for years hid the pain and suffering i carried. my childhood wasn't all bed of roses. my mother was abusive. somehow, i rose from it. then in 2011, after i watched my father pass away, i fell into a deep depression. my rock and my protector gone. one month after his passing my sister & her husband brutally beat me up. returning back to work from my injuries earlier than i was supposed to be, my supervisor & manager threatened and bullied me at work. i asked myself,"if i'm just here to be used and abused, why am i still living? is this my destiny?" i ended up with ptsd. i became submissive, suicidal and zero trust in people. i was broken both mentally and physically. 5 yrs later i started lifting weights. i started to trust my friends i met at the gym. not only they taught me how to be strong physically but mentally as well. i was starting to feel and look stronger day by day month by month. i got to test out my new found strength. a person i had met attacked me and wouldn't stop. at first i became submissive and took the abuse then eventually i snapped and punched the person three times and took off. days later, i realized i am strong enough to fight back! my hardwork in the gym and my new friends helped me achieve my goals and since i want more!!! more strength, more gains! people ask me why i lift weights? am i not worried i'll look like a guy? get bulky? ha! bring it on! lifting weights not only help me physically but mentally as well and if it wasn't for my strong friends behind me, i would still be that submissive broken person. today my smile is genuine happiness. i'm so proud of myself & the only pain i have is after an intensive workout lifting weights. ğŸ™

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
introducing our closing plenary panelists at the #likho indian lgbtq media summit in mumbai on december 15, 2018 for the panel discussion - "beyond #metoo: creating an equal, diverse, inclusive & safe media workplace". the panelists are vinta nanda, parmesh shahani, apsara reddy and anuraadha tewari. the panel will be moderated by urmi chanda vaz. 
likho is an initiative of bombay dost and humsafar trust to promote fair and inclusive representation of the lgbtq community in indian media. the event this year is presented by blued.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company â€œweaponisedâ€ the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how usersâ€™ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms â€“ facebook, in particular â€“ were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaignâ€™s lesser reported â€œweapons of mass destructionâ€. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someoneâ€™s personality. a userâ€™s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call â€œpopulist political signallingâ€. cambridge analytica, which wasÂ shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn
